<HL>
   Gm Says Future
   Of ZR-1 Corvette
   Is Now in Doubt
   ---
   Touted Model Is the Latest
   In a String of Image Cars
   To Stumble in Market
   ----
   By Neal Templin
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
11/11/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<CO>
   GM HMC
</CO>
<MS>
CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)
</MS>
<IN>
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<RE>
FAR EAST (FE)
JAPAN (JA)
MICHIGAN (MI)
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
PACIFIC RIM (PRM)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   DETROIT -- General Motors Corp. is considering killing its
highly touted ZR-1 Corvette because of sputtering sales for
the 375-horsepower sports car.
   A Chevrolet spokesman confirmed reports by suppliers and
Auto Week magazine that the future of the $65,000 Chevrolet
model is "under review." Chevrolet is looking at alternatives
to killing the ZR-1, including boosting the power of its
high-tech, eight-cylinder engine to rekindle its appeal, he
said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But by acknowledging that the ZR-1's future is in doubt,
GM risks turning a car that was supposed to burnish the auto
maker's image into another emblem of disappointment.
   "The ZR-1 came into being for one reason only," says the
Chevrolet spokesman. "And that was to add luster to the
Corvette line and, by extension, to the entire Chevrolet
line."
   Instead, the ZR-1, nicknamed "King of the Hill," is the
latest in a string of heavily promoted GM image cars to
stumble in the market. In 1988, GM was forced to kill its
Pontiac Fiero after the plastic-bodied car's propensity to
catch fire killed demand. Earlier this year, GM pulled the
plug on its slow-selling Buick Reatta two-seater. GM
continues to produce the Cadillac Allante, a two-seater
designed to compete with exclusive Jaguar and Mercedes-Benz
roadsters. But GM has heavily discounted the $57,000 Allante
in the past because of disappointing sales.
   GM isn't alone in having trouble selling high-priced,
exotic cars in the recessionary auto market. Honda Motor
Co.'s aluminum-bodied Acura NSX sports car, which came out a
year ago to rave reviews, now appears to be struggling. Honda
sold just 86 NSX models in October, down from 270 cars a year
ago. A Honda spokesman conceded that demand is soft, although
he said the drop in NSX sales also reflects a slow launch of
1992 models.
   But many of the Corvette ZR-1's problems appear to be of
GM's making. Like the NSX, the ZR-1 started out red hot when
it was introduced in 1989, with some dealers charging
premiums of thousands of dollars above its $58,995 list price
back then. "It was absolutely wild in the beginning,"
remembers Dan Bischof, general manager of Ed Morse Chevrolet
near Fort Lauderdale, Fla. "People were calling us from all
over the U.S."
   But a year ago, GM changed the rear end of the standard
Corvette so that it looked like the ZR-1. Then, Mercury
Marine, which makes the ZR-1's 32-valve, eight-cylinder
motor, stopped production for more than three months to fix a
design flaw that was causing some ZR-1 engines to self
destruct. When production started again in April 1990, demand
for the car had chilled.
   The crowning blow came this fall, when GM put a more
powerful motor in the regular 1992 Corvette. The base
Corvette, priced at about $34,000, now accelerates to 60
miles per hour in just five seconds, only a step slower than
the sizzling 4.3-second zero-to-60 time of a ZR-1 that costs
nearly twice as much.
   The result: Dealers are now heavily discounting the ZR-1,
bad news for collectors who bought early models in hopes they
would appreciate. "We have them in stock and we've got
relatively few buyers," says Ed Morse Chevrolet's Mr.
Bischof.
   Without giving specific figures, Chevrolet says ZR-1 sales
are down, even though overall Corvette sales rose 9% in
October from a year ago. Moreover, production of the ZR-1 is
being scaled back. Mercury Marine's Stillwater, Okla.,
factory is producing just six ZR-1 engines a day, a third of
capacity. GM had expected the ZR-1 would account for 10% of
total Corvette production this year, but the company
spokesman says the actual percentage is less.
   Mercury Marine workers, meanwhile, want to save the car.
They even rigged up experimental engines that produce over
500 horsepower, says James Skalitzky, a manager in the
factory. However, those engines don't meet federal pollution
standards, he said.
</TEXT>
