<HEAD>1990 Chevrolets Introduced; New Lincoln Town Car Rolls Off Line</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos DT1, DT3 of Aug. 23</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A distinct identity for Chevrolet's Geo line of
small vehicles still hasn't been developed, nearly a year after the
first of the cars were introduced, a company executive says.
   Chevrolet General Manager Jim Perkins said Wednesday the GM
division is about halfway through its process of developing its Geo
franchise.
   The company is walking a narrow path between selling and
servicing the three Geo cars and one truck at Chevrolet dealers and
fostering a separate image for the nameplate.
   Geo cars were introduced in January. Since then, one model, the
Spectrum, has been dropped and two, the Metro and Storm, have been
added.
   Separate Geo signs are going up at dealerships and some Chevrolet
dealers are taking out space in commercial telephone books in the
G's to encourage the brand distinction.
   Also, Chevrolet's well-known ``Heartbeat of America'' advertising
theme, going into its fourth year, will not be used in Geo ads.
Instead, those ads feature the theme, ``Getting to know Geo,'' to
the tune of ``Getting to Know You,'' from the play ``The King and
I.''
   ``The Geo imagery is going to become more focused than it has
been in the past,'' Perkins said.
   Perkins, speaking during the introduction of the Chevrolet lineup
for 1990, also said GM is ready to give Chevrolet dealers a hand in
marketing the Geo and will boost the potential dealer profit margin
on Geo cars and trucks.
   GM has been criticized for failing to give consumers a clear
picture of its new line of cars. For the coming model year, there
will be three Geo cars _ the Storm, Prizm and Metro and one
sport-utility vehicle _ the Tracker.
   The Metro is made by Suzuki Motor Co. Ltd. in Japan; the Tracker
is made in Canada by the GM-Suzuki joint venture Canadian-American
Manufacturing Inc.; the Prizm is made in Fremont, Calif., at the
GM-Toyota joint venture New United Motor Manufacturing Inc.; and the
Storm is made in Fujisawa, Japan, by Isuzu Motors Ltd.
   Eighty-four percent of the 4,800 Chevrolet dealers have agreed to
sell Geos. GM denied reports earlier this year that some dealers
were pressured into taking on Geo in return for getting a crack at
selling the new Corvette ZR-1, production of which begins later this
month in Bowling Green, Ky.
   Perkins said the ZR-1, with a 370-horsepower engine that can push
the car from 0 to 60 mph in 4.2 seconds, will sell for $58,995.
About 3,000 of the cars will be available in the United States
during the 1990 model year, mainly because of restraints by the
engine maker, Mercury Marine.
   An undetermined number of ZR-1 Corvettes will be sold in Europe,
Perkins said.
   Separately Wednesday, Ford Motor Co. rolled the first 1990
Lincoln Town Car off the assembly line in Wixom, Mich., with a
ceremony complete with a cake the shape of a 1989 Town Car. The new
version, which will be introduced formally Oct. 5, is a longer,
slightly rounded version of the 1989 model.
