<LEADPARA>  General Motors Corp. is making only half as many of its sleek $64,000 Corvette
ZR1s after stopping production for nearly four months due to a faulty engine
part.;    The Bowling Green, Ky., assembly plant is building just nine ZR1s a
day because of a shortage of corrected camshafts, a component that regulates
fuel flow into the engine, Chevrolet spokesman Tom Hoxie said Monday.;    The
original oversized camshaft caused the engines to overheat under certain
conditions.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FLAW DELAYS CORVETTE PRODUCTION  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The problem was discovered in November when seven of the car's
370-horsepower engines broke down as workers revved the engines at the
assembly plant's shipping yard, Hoxie said.;    Chevrolet located the entire
batch of 500 ZR1s with engines made by Mercury Marine in Stillwater, Okla.,
all at dealerships and in the shipping yard, and found that 17 had defective
engines, Hoxie said.;    There was no official recall as production was halted
from early December through March 16. The plant makes all types of Corvettes
and there were no layoffs due to the defect, he said.;    If it were not for
the production halt, about 1,500 cars would have been built in that time. The
normal production is 3,600 a year.;    "It's taking a while to catch up,"
Hoxie said. "Obviously it's going to affect the annual production.";    The
shortage may cause dealerships to raise the prices, an auto analyst said.;   
Chris Cedergren of J.D. Power &amp; Associates in Agoura Hills, Calif., said the
No. 1 automaker handled the situation well by correcting the problem at the
assembly plant level, rather than selling the cars anyway and letting the
dealerships handle recalls.;    The ZR1 has a 32-valve, eight-cylinder
aluminum engine that can zoom from zero to 60 mph in 4.3 seconds.;    They
discovered the engines' camshafts were slightly oversized, but found that the
breakdowns were due to a combination of situations. The engines that blew out
had never been started up before and were stored in below-freezing
temperatures, Hoxie said.;    "There are a series of circumstances that had to
exist for it to happen," Hoxie said.;    John Harris, sales manager at Vermont
Chevrolet in Los Angeles, said Monday that his business was not affected by
the stopped production.;    "I didn't have a single one in stock," he said.
"Not a lot of people can afford those."  </TEXT>
