<HEAD>Chrysler Ready To Announce New, Pumped-Up Sports Car</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. has decided to produce its
proposed Viper sports car featuring a 10-cylinder engine, a source
said Tuesday, a move apparently designed to polish the image of the
struggling carmaker.
   The Dodge Viper, equipped with an engine originally designed for
truck use, will go into extremely low-volume production late next
year for the 1992 model year, said a company source speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   ``Anything that shows people that Dodge is back in the
performance business is good news,'' said David Slone, general
sales manager of Lynn Hickey Dodge in Oklahoma City.
   A Viper prototype was introduced last year at an annual auto
show in Detroit and drew huge crowds. The two-seat convertible is a
throwback to the era of sleek, muscular sports cars with few
electronic gadgets.
   The prototype has been part of a six-city tour this spring
during which Chrysler executives have touted the quality of the
company's vehicles, comparing them favorably with those made by
Japanese automakers.
   The tour winds up Friday in Los Angeles, where Chrysler Chairman
Lee Iacocca is expected to announce that the Viper will go into
production.
   Such an announcement would come as Chrysler car sales and
profits slip and as the company struggles to carve $1.5 billion
from its annual $26 billion budget.
   The cost of the Viper project hasn't been pinpointed. Despite
that expense at a time when the company is trimming back, analysts
and dealers on Tuesday were enthusiastic about the project, not
only because of the exotic nature of the car, but because of the
traffic it can draw to dealerships.
   Slone said he already has noticed an increase in traffic through
his showroom just because of media attention the Viper has received.
   ``We've had people wanting to put deposits down on it,'' he said.
   The car's price won't be announced until just before it hits the
showrooms. AutoWeek magazine said it could be in the $40,000 range.
   The Viper would be entering the exotic sports-car market,
broadly comprised of the Corvette ZR-1, some BMWs and Porsches.
   No firm performance statistics were available, but AutoWeek
magazine reported that with the V-10 engine, the Viper could go
from a standing start to 100 mph in less than 10 seconds. The ZR-1,
the hottest Corvette ever, takes 11.5 seconds to get to 100 mph,
according to a Road &amp; Track magazine road test.
   ``There is an enthusiasts' market out there,'' said auto analyst
Mary Anne Sudol of Fitch Investors Service Inc. in New York. ``I
think there is room in the market for it (Viper). I think the hot
cars carry fairly nice (profit) margins and you wouldn't have to
put an incentive on them.
   ``I think it will make people sit up and notice Chrysler even
though there aren't many (Vipers) around. It's what they can do in
styling and performance.''
   The prototype has distinctive door panels with chrome-plated
exhaust pipes running below them. A spy photo appearing in the June
issue of Car and Driver magazine shows a Viper without the
side-mounted pipes.
   The source said all major components of the car would be made by
Chrysler. The source declined to reveal the final assembly site,
but said it would be an existing Chrysler factory.
   Production figures weren't available, but it could be as low as
a few hundred a year. By contrast, General Motors Corp. sold about
24,000 Corvettes last year, before the introduction of the ZR-1
model.
   Chrysler has said that the Viper was the first project to result
from the carmaker's conceptual design and rendering system. The
computer-driven system could cut by 25 percent the amount of time
needed to bring a totally new car to market, Chrysler officials
said.
</TEXT>
