   Rain Poses Acid Test
   For Auto Exteriors
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   ACID RAIN threatens lakes and forests, many scientists
say, but what about cars?
   An Environmental Protection Agency study finds that acid
rain etches dull-looking spots into a car's paint. That's
because the acids in rainwater don't evaporate, but instead
become more concentrated as the raindrops dry. Heat from the
sun or engine increases the damage.
   The spots are hard to detect on light-colored vehicles but
are easily found on darker cars, especially black ones. The
spots are also easier to see under fluorescent lights than in
sunlight.
   Car owners living on the East Coast are most likely to see
the dull spots on their cars, because the region's rain is
more acidic than in the rest of the country. However, people
living elsewhere will probably detect spots if they examine
their cars closely.
   "There is little doubt that the problem is widespread,"
says Edward Edney, an EPA researcher who has studied the
effects of acid rain and fog. The only cure is prevention:
keeping cars out of rain or fog, or drying them immediately
after exposure.
   Some auto makers are working with paint suppliers to find
a solution. General Motors and Chrysler, for example, each
have developed a clear protective coating to go on top of
paint. GM says its coating, developed about two years ago, is
effective at spot prevention even though it wasn't developed
specifically to combat acid rain. The coating is currently
being used on about half of its vehicles, GM says, and will
be put on more in the future.
   Chrysler, which introduced its coating in February, says
it was designed to protect against acid rain and works well
in most regions of the country. Chrysler uses it in three
assembly plants and expects to use it in most of its
facilities by July.
                                                                                                       

   They Help You to Pick
   Peaches, Not Lemons
                                                                                                       

   THE HIGH PRICE of new cars has many buyers looking for
used ones, but how do you avoid getting taken? Try calling an
expert.
   A growing number of firms will, for a fee, inspect used
cars and tell potential buyers how much they're actually
worth. Car Checkers of America, for example, inspects 3,500
electrical and mechanical components of used cars. The
company also determines whether a car has been involved in an
accident and whether it's starting to rust. The inspection
costs between $75 and $100, and takes about an hour.
   "Just listening and looking isn't enough anymore," says
Lee S. Geller, vice president of Car Checkers, in
Bridgewater, N.J. Business has jumped 30% since the recession
began, he says. Auto Critic of America, in Dallas, performs a
90-point inspection for between $54 and $79, grading such
components as the battery, air conditioner and transmission
on a scale of A (high quality) to F (poor quality). Patrick
A. Ludwick, president, expects the two-year-old company to
earn its first profit this year.
   Most companies that inspect used cars send technicians to
the vehicle's location, even if it's a dealer's lot. While it
seems this might irk dealers, the companies claim they're
welcome. "Many dealers pay us" to determine the quality and
value of used-car trade-ins, Mr. Geller says.
   "These companies can serve a purpose," says Marion Gorton
of the Michigan attorney general's office. "The inspection
gives consumers the opportunity to find out what's obviously
wrong with the car." The companies don't do repairs, and most
require customers to sign a disclaimer releasing the firms of
liability in case a highly rated car turns out to be a lemon.
                                                                                                       

   It's Very, Very Fast,
   But It Isn't Moving
                                                                                                       

   GENERAL MOTORS' highly touted Corvette ZR-1 once fetched
as much as $80,000 -- a whopping $15,862 above its suggested
retail price. But now, some dealers are having trouble
selling the car -- even below retail.
   The ZR-1, nicknamed King of the Hill, was a hit with
auto-enthusiast magazines. They loved the 32-valve,
eight-cylinder, 370-horsepower aluminum engine that zips the
car from 0 to 60 miles per hour in a bone-jarring 4.3
seconds. GM won't disclose the number of ZR-1 models -- as
opposed to regular Corvettes -- it has sold this year, but
concedes that sales have slowed.
   So why has demand for GM's most exotic and expensive car
cooled? The auto maker's Chevrolet division contends that
after a year on the market, the ZR-1 is no longer a new, hot
item. "It's a natural thing in the marketplace," says a
spokesman for the division, who also cites the effects of the
recession.
   But a mechanical snafu also may have damped consumer
enthusiasm. GM had to stop selling the car for 3 1/2 months
while correcting a problem -- it turned out to be some
defective camshafts -- that caused some engines to overheat
and "seize," or self-destruct.
                                                                                                       

   Buy a Trendy Couch
   And Get a Car to Match
                                                                                                       

   WANT TO KNOW which car colors will be hot in few years? Go
shopping for a new sofa or drapes.
   The colors of home furnishings are one of the leading
indicators that car companies track to figure out colors to
paint their cars. Turquoise, a trendy color today on sporty
cars, first showed up in furniture in the Southwest. White,
the leading color today, also has made a comeback in home
appliances, such as refrigerators.
   Right now, auto makers are deciding colors for the 1994
models. Turquoise and aqua (along with perennial favorites
red, white and blue) are expected to be popular still.
</TEXT>
