<HEAD>Road Tour Kicks Off Corvette Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From the 700 Corvettes in the 20-mile
road tour to the 200 radio-controlled models in their own road
race, there was something for every Corvette fan at the Bloomington
Gold-Corvettes USA show.
   There's also the coveted Bloomington Gold certificate for the
Chevrolet two-seaters preserved in or restored to 95 percent of the
showroom condition.
   And there's a classification for ``Survivors,'' Corvettes at
least 20 years old that have been largely unrestored but preserved
well enough to serve as models for those doing restoration.
   In excellent condition, a Corvette built between 1963 and 1967
could fetch up to $100,000, says David Burroughs, president of the
show.
   Some custom-built racing models go even higher. Five Grand Sport
Corvettes produced in 1963 exclusively for racing are worth up to
$1 million, Burroughs says.
   Next on the most-valuable list would be the L88 Corvette, says
Burroughs. Produced from 1967 to 1969, and also built for racing,
L88s sell for $100,000 to $500,000. Only about 200 of the cars were
built.
   The demand for Corvettes is changing, though, Burroughs says.
The 'Vettes of the 1950s are popular with people who grew up then,
but as baby boomers become able to invest in the cars, the 1963-67
models are becoming more popular.
   About 35,000 people and as many as 5,000 Corvettes were expected
for this year's show, which concluded Sunday with judging and the
radio-controlled finals.
</TEXT>
