<HEAD>Big Engines, Luxury Cars Trendy Items at Geneva Motor Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Extravagant, sporty cars with powerful engines and
fancy technical frills are headline items at the 1989 Geneva Motor
Show, reflecting the auto industry's buoyant confidence.
   Organizers of the annual show, which opened Thursday and runs
until March 19, cite the worldwide comeback of the top-priced sports
car and renewed competition in the compact model range as this
year's major themes.
   Billed as the European show most representative of the global
industry, Geneva is considered a prime testing ground for automakers
because of Switzerland's liberal import policy and lack of a
domestic industry, which make it a highly competitive market.
   Opel, Volkswagen and Toyota were the top-selling makes in
Switzerland last year, followed by Ford Europe, Fiat and France's
Peugeot.
   The industry's optimism is evident after low oil prices and a
continuing economic boom in Western countries spurred world car
production to its fourth straight record high last year.
   The show appears aimed at Western Europe, where environmental
worries had an impact on the car industry through the mid-1980s.
   But that concern seems to be waning. The European Community has
launched a drive to cut harmful exhaust emissions, and use of
pollution-reducing catalytic converters, though hardly universal, is
rising.
   At Geneva, Mercedes unveiled its revived SL roadster series,
aimed at recapturing affluent buyers from its West German rival BMW,
whose 7-series is considered the leader in the upscale market.
   BMW's display featured the M5, a model introduced last fall with
a 315-horsepower six-cylinder engine.
   Not to be outdone, General Motors Corp. offered an updated
Corvette sports model with a 32-valve V-8. The Corvette ZR1, is
expected to cost about $50,000. GM officials have not said when the
ZR1 will go on sale in the United States or Europe.
   Porsche, the West German maker of prestige sports cars,
highlighted a new automatic tire pressure monitoring system in its
top-of-the-line 928-S4 model, which lists for $74,900.
   Volvo of Sweden offered a heated steering wheel for its
higher-priced cars.
   Recognizing the continuing vast market potential for affordable
compact cars especially in Europe, Ford Motor Co.'s West German
division premiered a complete revamp of its successful Fiesta
hatchback, of which more than 4.5 million have been built since 1976.
   Main innovations include four-door models, more passenger space
and an updated body. Prices have remained stable, ranging from about
$8,200 for the basic models to $12,500 for a sporty three-door.
   Swiss President Jean-Pascal Delamuraz said in opening the 59th
show that the event was a ``convincing denial'' of a clash between
economic and environmental goals.
</TEXT>
