<LEADPARA>  WILL a nation weaned on collecting baseball cards be as enthusiastic about
filling shoe boxes with pictures of the '53 Corvette, '63 Sting Ray and '91
King of the Hill?;    A pair of brothers think so.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Drive  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  WANNA TRADE THAT STING RAY FOR A CONVERTIBLE?  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Collect-A-Card of Greenville, S.C., has come up with a set of 100 Chevrolet
Corvette collector/trading cards called the Vette Set. The 100 glossy,
full-color cards depict every Corvette built as well as some that made it to
dream-car status but never into production.;    They arrived at the San
Francisco Card Exchange last week. Vette Set cards will be sold in packs of 10
for $1.25 to $1.50.;    Neil and John Connor formed Collect-A-Card about a
year ago. Their first trading card set was of Professional Bowling Association
stars. Then Neil, a former marketing executive with an organ company, and
John, a retired postal clerk, decided to move into cars.;    "There's 'Vette
people everywhere -- those who own one, once owned one or who just like the
car," John said. "There's more than 7,000 Corvette clubs across the country.";
   Collect-A-Card has a five-year non-exclusive agreement with Chevrolet to
produce the cards. It paid a hefty license fee and will pay a royalty for
cards sold.;    The cards feature a photo of each car on the front and some
statistics and special features on the back. Whereas baseball cards provide a
rundown on the player's stats, including times at bat, hits and lifetime
average, the 'Vette cards list the total number assembled of that particular
model, base price when new, optional body styles if any, colors, engine
options, and vital serial numbers cherished by car collectors.;    Though the
brothers hope to capitalize on the collecting habits of 'Vette enthusiasts,
neither owns a 'Vette. Neil drives a Honda Acura and John a GMC Jimmy.;  IF
YOU'RE INTERESTED; To contact Collect-A-Card, call (800) 243-7273.  </TEXT>
