<HEAD>Old-Time Parade For Astronauts To Feature Vintage Corvettes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COCOA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Astronauts from the shuttle Discovery
will ride in vintage Corvettes once driven by speed-loving pioneers
in the nation's space program for a nostalgic parade Monday in this
Space Coast town.
   From 1967 to 1971, a Melbourne Chevrolet dealership gave
astronauts the cars of their choice for $1 a year under a
promotional lease.
   Almost all chose Corvettes and they were easily spotted. Each
was red, white or blue, with two stripes in the other patriotic
colors slashed across the hood and trunk.
   ``Being the hot-footed test pilots they were _ craving for speed
_ it was only natural for them to choose Corvettes,'' said Jim
Falkowski of Fort Lauderdale, who paid $25,000 for astronaut Gus
Grissom's 1967 convertible Corvette and has been offered $52,000
for it.
   Grissom, one of the seven original Mercury astronauts, drove the
car until he died in the Apollo 1 launch pad fire in 1967.
   A 1968 Corvette originally owned by astronaut Alan Shepard will
be used in Monday's parade, along with two 1988 Corvette
convertibles on loan from Jim Rathmann Chevrolet in Melbourne.
   The five-mile motorcade, from Patrick Air Force Base to a Cocoa
Beach motel, will be modeled after a half-dozen parades held in
Cocoa Beach for astronauts during the 1960s.
   Thousands of people lined the streets from the air base to Cape
Canaveral during those parades.
   ``It was like a big homecoming parade,'' said Bob Murkshe, Cocoa
Beach mayor from 1963 to 1972. ``The astronauts would ride in open
convertibles and people would line the streets and wave flags.
   ``We were all working in the space program then.''
   About 500,000 people watched the launching of Discovery on Sept.
28. The shuttle fleet had been grounded for 32 months since the
January 1986 explosion of the shuttle Challenger, which killed all
seven crew members aboard.
</TEXT>
