<LEADPARA>  IN 1970, there were hot cars, and then there were VERY hot cars.;    Just
about every dealer showroom was bursting with big-engine automobiles capable
of peeling the tread off a set of tires in seconds.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Drive  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HORSEPOWER RULED THE ROADS IN THE 1970 MUSCLE-CAR
CRAZE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Vintage Cars  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     There were Road Runners, Super Bees, Chargers, Barracudas and Challengers
at the Chrysler outlets.;    Ford and Mercury had Torino Talladega GTs,
Montego GTs, Mustangs and Cougars.;    At General Motors, there were GTOs,
442s, Gran Sports, Chevelle Super Sports, Firebirds and Camaros.;    In their
usual trim, these cars were rockets -- capable of 14-second quarter-mile times
on the skinny stock tires of the era.;    But for some discerning buyers, the
base models of these hot rods were not enough. The name of the game was to
out-horsepower your neighbor, and Detroit was only too happy to oblige.;    So
listed on the option sheets were several upgraded engines, all with amazing
amounts of horsepower.;    Chevrolet was particularly astute at playing the
engine-option game, particularly on its Camaros, Corvettes and Chevelles.;   
That the Camaro and the Corvette had many engine options was not surprising --
they were, after all, sports cars designed to appeal to the high-octane
crowd.;    But the Chevelle was, in the beginning, a staid, mid-size passenger
car, targeted at a young family that couldn't afford the full-sized Impala or
Caprice.;    Introduced in 1964, the Chevelle was available in 13 model
choices, ranging from station wagons to four-door sedans to convertibles.;   
Since Detroit was just waking up to the sales power of high-performance
models, the Chevelle was also offered in Super Sport trim.;    Called the
Malibu SS, it came with bucket seats, upgraded vinyl interior trim and a
center transmission console. And when the right option box was checked, a
300-horsepower 327-cubic-inch V-8 was added.;    Two years later, the hot
setup in the Chevelle was the SS-396, a car that epitomized the mid-size
muscle-car craze. The SS-396 was, by all accounts, the best-selling model when
compared to Road Runners, GTOs and the like.;    In base tune, the SS-396
produced 325 horsepower, but power-fiends could order versions that produced
350 and 375 horsepower.;    The SS-396 survived as the top-dog Chevelle until
the 1970 model year, when the largest-displacement Chevy engine ever built --
the 454 -- was offered alongside the standard 396.;    And again, the engine
mavens at Chevrolet obliged the speed crowd by offering two versions of the
SS-454. The base engine, called the LS-5 -- which was its designation on the
order form -- was rated at 425 horsepower.;    The LS-5 was awesome even by
today's standards, but some Chevelle buyers craved more and, they ordered the
454-cubic-inch engine designated as the LS-6.;    Conservatively rated at 450
horsepower, the LS-6 came with solid valve lifters, aluminum cylinder heads,
an aluminum intake manifold and an 11.25:1 compression ratio.;    Available
with either a Turbo Hydramatic or M-22 four-speed transmission, the SS-454 was
put into several thousand Chevelles and El Caminos -- the snazzy pickup truck
derivative of the Chevelle.;    Road tests in 1970 verified that a showroom
stock LS-6 Chevelle could turn the quarter-mile in a few ticks over 13
seconds.;    It was a performance high that would never be duplicated in the
Chevelle, as government regulations, oil embargoes and insurance worries
deflated the horsepower boom in the early 1970s.;    While the SS-396 remains
one of the best-known muscle cars of the 1960s, the SS-454 LS-6 Chevelle is
highly valued by Chevy collectors.  </TEXT>
