<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency has
ordered General Motors Corp. to recall almost half a million 1985
cars and light trucks sold under the Chevrolet, Pontiac and GMC
nameplates, EPA said today.
   The cars exceed federal standards for carbon monoxide exhaust
emissions and for evaporated gasoline, EPA said.
   Such orders are rare and are generally a sign the agency and the
manufacturer could not agree on something, such as the cause of the
problem, its scope, the necessary repair or terms of the recall.
Most recalls are made voluntarily.
   GM's Washington office said the company would have a statement
later.
   The company has 45 days either to request a public hearing to
contest the order, or to submit a repair plan for EPA's approval
before notices are mailed to owners.
   EPA said the affected vehicles are equipped with 5.0-liter (305
cubic inches) and 5.7-liter (350 cubic inches) engines and were
sold as the Chevrolet Impala, Caprice Classic, Camaro, Monte Carlo
and El Camino; the Pontiac Firebird, Bonneville, Grand Prix and
Parisienne; and the GMC Caballero. Models sold in California, which
are built to stricter standards, are included.
   The excessive emissions are in part the result of defects in a
thermal vacuum switch in the evaporation control system, EPA said.
But the agency said simple replacement of the switch may not
completely remedy the problem and further repairs, which it did not
specify, may be necessary.
   Last year, GM recalled more than a million vehicles from the
1982 and 1983 model years for similar problems.
   GM also is recalling about 4,900 1988 Chevrolet Corvettes to fix
defective wheel welds that could cause the wheel center to separate
from the rim during braking or cornering.
   The automaker said Wednesday it is also recalling about 460 1987
GMC and Chevrolet full-size vans to correct fuel tank filler pipes
that could cause fuel to leak during refueling or turning.
   No accidents or injuries have been linked to either problem, GM
said. Vehicle owners are being notified of the recall by dealers,
who will correct the problems at no charge, the company said.
   The Corvettes, all equipped with 17-inch wheels, may be missing
a weld on some wheels, GM said. The condition could result in
partial loss of steering control and a sudden changed in vehicle
direction, the automaker said.
</TEXT>
