<HEAD>GM Recalls 147,200 Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. on Wednesday recalled about
147,200 cars and vans in five separate actions for problems that
include the possibility of parts breaking in rear suspensions of
some Corvettes.
   The recall included 46,000 1988- and 1989-model Corvettes with
rear-wheel tie rod assemblies that may break, causing a loss of
control.
   GM spokesman Tom Pyden said the automaker wasn't aware of any
deaths or major injuries because of any of the problems.
   The automaker also recalled:
   _About 1,100 1990-model Pontiac Grand Prix SE Turbo cars for
removal of a rear spring heat shield which may puncture the fuel
tank in a collision.
   _About 84,000 1987-89 Chevrolet Corsica sedans because of door
hinge problems which could affect the car's ability to withstand a
side-impact crash.
   _About 10,000 1990 Buick Riviera and Cadillac Eldorado and
Seville cars with potentially sticky rear shoulder safety belt
assemblies.
   _Nearly 6,100 1987-89 Chevrolet and GMC Step Vans built for
commercial delivery for replacement of a seat pedestal which may
not be able to hold the seat or a passenger during a crash.
   GM said owners were being notified by mail. Inspections and
repairs will be performed for free.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

