<LP>
   OAKLAND, Calif. -- A California jury awarded $6.1 million
to a man who said his injuries in an auto accident resulted
from the defective roof design of General Motors Corp.'s
Chevrolet Corvette.
   On Tuesday, the Contra Costa County Superior Court held GM
liable for most of the injuries suffered by Sherill Smothers,
30 years old, after his Corvette was hit from behind and
flipped over in a 1988 accident. The roof collapsed and Mr.
Smothers's neck was fractured, permanently injuring his
spinal cord.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Although the Corvette's roof met federal safety
guidelines, the jury found GM 80% responsible for Mr.
Smothers's injuries. Accordingly, GM is liable for $5.5
million of the award. The other driver is responsible for the
remainder.
   Yesterday, GM officials said that the Corvette's roof
wasn't defectively designed and that they will appeal the
jury's decision.
</TEXT>
