<HEAD>Car Thieves Prefer Camaros, Corvettes And Porsches, Study Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car thieves like sporty special models and in
some cases they're interested in only the radio, says an insurance
industry study. The cars safest from theft are small- and mid-sized
domestics, especially station wagons.
   A report by the Highway Loss Data Institute said Thursday that
the likelihood of theft ranges widely among cars and that the most
frequent targets are Volkswagens where the radio is easy to steal
and is a powerful lure.
   A study of 1985-87 model cars found seven Volkswagens among the
11 car models with the highest rate of theft claims. All 11 cars
were imports, and in many cases thieves were only interested in the
radios, said the report.
   The radios ``are easily accessible,'' said Rick Elder, vice
president of the insurance group, in an interview. ``You can snap
them out of one car and easily put them into another. It's a very
attractive theft target.''
   But when thieves are out to steal an entire car they are likely
to pick expensive sporty models, including a number of U.S. cars,
the study concluded. High on the list is the Porsche 911 Coupe,
followed by the Chevrolet Corvette and the Chevrolet Camaro, the
report said.
   It said sports and speciality cars continued to account ``for an
overwhelming share of total theft losses.'' While these cars
account for about 15 percent of the total number of cars insured,
they represent 40 percent of the dollars paid on insurance claims
because of theft.
   The least likely cars to be stolen or broken into are small and
mid-sized domestic models, led by the Mercury Lynx, said the
insurance group.
   According to the report, the Volkwagen GTI, which had the
highest theft rate, was nearly 70 times as likely to be the target
of a thief as the Lynx.
   Other cars with little interest from thieves, according to the
study, were the Mercury Grand Marquis station wagon and Mercury
Topaz, the Plymouth Colt Vista wagon and Pontiac Sunbird wagon.
   The study covered 1985-87 models.
   Among vans, pickup trucks and utility vehicles, the 1985 Jeep
CJ-7 and the 1986 and 1987 Suzuki Samurai had the highest
likelihood for theft. Small pickup trucks generally had the lowest
theft rate.
   Some cars lost the interest of thieves after their design
changed or in some cases security devices were installed, the
report said. For example the theft rate for the Chevrolet Corvette
declined somewhat after new security system was put in the 1986
model.
   But it said design changes in the Mazda RX-7 and Toyota Celica
resulted in sharply lower theft losses in 1986 and 1987. Elder
attributed the decline to thieves not having a market for the newly
designed parts.
   ``The demand for the stolen parts hasn't built up,'' he
suggested.
   Meanwhile, theft losses for the Buick Regal and Chevrolet Monte
Carlo, both of which adopted a more sporty look in 1987, increased
sharply that year, the report said.
   The report tracked theft losses during the first year of
availability for the 1987 models cars, the first two years of
availability for 1986 models and the first three years of
availability for 1985 models.
   The Highway Loss Data Institute, which is part of the Insurance
Institute for Highway Safety, gathers and processes a broad range
of insurance statistical data.
</TEXT>
